'''Brisote''' (also '''brisole''') is a term used to describe the northeast [[trade wind]] when it is blowing more strongly than usual over [[Cuba]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ixUYN_XCeJUC&pg=PA135&dq=brisote+wind&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMkt_FqPTTAhUKfiYKHfQLCuMQ6AEILDAC#v=onepage&q=brisote%20wind&f=false|title=1001 Questions Answered about the Weather|last=Forrester|first=Frank H.|date=1981|publisher=Courier Corporation|year=|isbn=9780486242187|location=|pages=135|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=-mwbAsxpRr0C&pg=PA469&dq=brisote+wind&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMkt_FqPTTAhUKfiYKHfQLCuMQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=brisote%20wind&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of World Climatology|last=Oliver|first=John E.|date=2008-04-23|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781402032646|language=en}}</ref> The typical strength of this wind is 9 m s<sup>−1</sup>; anything blowing at a stronger rate may be described as a brisote.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=WBN0CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA216&dq=brisote+wind&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMkt_FqPTTAhUKfiYKHfQLCuMQ6AEIMjAD#v=onepage&q=brisote%20wind&f=false|title=An Introduction to the Meteorology and Climate of the Tropics|last=Galvin|first=J. F. P.|date=2016-01-22|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=|isbn=9781119086246|location=|pages=216|language=en}}</ref> A brisote may be associated with [[tropical cyclone]]s passing north-east of the island.<ref name=":0" />

